In building a battery of toy Xsets for our directed graph embedding methods, the time has come to expand beyond the meager realm of 2-dimensional datasets, and into the vast (but still meager) world of 3d Xsets.

This notebook builds pointclouds resembling a sphere, a torus, and a paraboloid, and assigns each a flow field.

Flows

Here's a bunch of sample flows in 3 space, which can be adapted to a variety of manifolds, like the sphere, torus, hyperboloid. The flows in this section don't have anything to do with the geometry of the manifold, but simply prescribe arrows to the entire 3 plane.

Whirlpool

Our flow functions will involve radian-like coordinates, which use the angles of points relative to the origin

angle_x(X)

Returns angle in [0, 2pi] corresponding to each point X

Torus

The torus must be sampled delicately. Here, we use a rejection sampling method, with code taken from Riddle's Diffusion Curvature project. (See x.riddle.press/diffusion_curvature)

{% raw %}

rejection_sample_for_torus[source]

rejection_sample_for_torus(n, r, R)

{% endraw %} {% raw %}

directed_torus[source]

directed_torus(n=2000, c=2, a=1, flow_type='whirlpool', noise=None, seed=None, use_guide_points=False)

Sample n data points on a torus. Modified from tadasets.shapes â€” TaDAsets 0.1.0 documentation Uses rejection sampling.

In addition to the points, returns a "flow" vector at each point.

Parameters

n : int Number of data points in shape. c : float Distance from center to center of tube. a : float Radius of tube. flow_type, in ['whirlpool']

ambient : int, default=None Embed the torus into a space with ambient dimension equal to ambient. The torus is randomly rotated in this high dimensional space. seed : int, default=None Seed for random state.

{% endraw %} {% raw %}
